post_text:
Board of Education Meeting

Sep. 8, 2020

Starts at 6:30 PM

Cafeteria / Live-Stream

The Stockbridge Valley CSD Board of Education Meeting will take place in the cafeteria. Please be advised that NYS mandates no more than 50 people being allowed at any gathering. Therefore, there will be a maximum of 38 people allowed in person. Those in attendance will be required to wear a mask and fill out a survey form. The BOE meeting will also be live-streamed for the public on the Stockbridge Valley CSD YouTube Channel below. Comments and questions will be turned on and read at the board meeting, along with any in person comments.

https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCnxkpdEatH7m-l6pk_NYbjA/featured

Please visit our Board of Education page for meeting dates, Board Member information, and meeting minutes.

FAMILIES CAN REGISTER FOR A FREE THERMOMETER

Any family in Madison County with school age children can give Community Action Program of Madison County a call at 315-684-3144, phone extension 10, to register for a thermometer, while supplies last.

Income restrictions do apply- 200% of the federal poverty guidelines. After registering, families will be directed to provide proof of income to verify eligibility.

SVCS Families: Yearbooks are here!

We are so excited to be able to get them to you! Thank you for your purchase and for supporting the Yearbook club, and for your patience during this uniquely difficult year.

PICKUP for yearbooks is THURSDAY, July 30th, 2020

9-11 AM
1-3 PM
6-7 PM

Pull up by the tunnels in the upper parking lot and let one of us know the student's name you are picking up for and if it is Elementary or High School then we will bring it and put into your trunk.

Thank you so much for your cooperation. Please wear your mask while talking to the staff who are asking your information. This is greatly appreciated!

Connie Rasmussen - 2020 Yearbook Advisor
Questions please email me! crasmussen@stockbridgevalley.org

Hello Stockbridge Valley Families,

These are strange and hectic times. With everything going on we know it is easy to forget to take time for self-care. With that in mind the Stockbridge Valley ‚ÄúQuaranteam‚Äù has brought you a May Wellness Bingo Challenge.

How to play: Complete as many activities as you can by the end of May, and for each Bingo you complete (up to 4) you will be entered into a drawing for a free ice cream generously donated by Cone Masters! Send a picture of your final board to Andrea Stabak (HS Principal), astabak@stockbridgevalley.org, by May 31st.

We will hold a live drawing on Monday, June 1st (specific time TBD). Gift certificates will then be mailed to you.

1 entry for each of the following:

Diagonal

Horizontal

Vertical

Entire board

We would love to see some posts of you and your families completing some wellness challenges on the district‚Äôs Facebook page!

Childcare for Essential Employees in our Community

During this current health crisis, you may be considered an essential employee who is still required to work. Childcare placement may be available to essential employees if it is needed. Essential employees are those people who work in health care, are first responders, who work in grocery stores, in transportation, some construction fields, certain non-profit agencies and in food or supply distribution fields.

If you believe that you may qualify, please call the Oneida-Herkimer-Madison Child Care Resource Center at 315-223-7850 extension 222.

April is School Library Month

April is School Library Month and the Stockbridge Valley Central School District thanks Melissa Grogan! She works with both students and teachers to facilitate access to information in a wide variety of formats and introduces children and young adults to literature and other resources to broaden their horizons.

‚ÄúSchool librarians are teachers, instructing students in finding and using information effectively in this very confusing information age; they are managers of the library program, space, and collection, with the goal of making everyone in their school feel included and welcome, and they are purveyors of a love of reading, which results in emotional well-being and lifelong literacy, among other things. They are critical to every school‚Äôs eco-system,‚Äù said Susan LeBlanc, Coordinator of the Madison-Oneida BOCES School Library System/CIS

CHILDCARE FOR ESSENTIAL EMPLOYEES IN OUR COMMUNITY

During this current health crisis, you may be considered an essential employee who is still required to work. Childcare placement may be available to essential employees if it is needed. Essential employees are those people who work in health care, are first responders, who work in grocery stores, in transportation, some construction fields, certain non-profit agencies and in food or supply distribution fields. If you believe that you may qualify, please call the Oneida-Herkimer-Madison Child Care Resource Center at 315-223-7850 extension 222.

The Mental Health Association in New York State (MHANYS) invites families and caregivers to join our webinar...

Coping With a Crisis
Thursday, March 26 from 12:30 to 1:00 pm

This webinar is presented as part of our 2020 monthly educational series for families and caregivers. This timely edition will help families to cope with our current situation, as well with the many common crises families often experience.

Most families will experience a crisis (illness, loss, natural disaster, etc.) at some point. Whether it is a situation that impacts just your family or something impacting the entire community, families are affected in many ways. This webinar will provide the knowledge and tools to promote whole family wellness during a time of crisis: recognition of stress indicators, the development of coping strategies and positive communication.

Please share with families in your community and stay tuned for more webinars!

https://register.gotowebinar.com/register/8231715208941001228

Stockbridge Valley Central School students Rachel Mennig, 10th grader and Tim Bernet, 7th grader attended Legislative Education Day on February 4th

BRiDGES and Herkimer, Madison and Oneida county Reality Check youth were at the Capitol February 4, 2020, talking with lawmakers about the success of the state‚Äôs Tobacco Control Program about lowering the average smoking rate to 12.8%. They also talked about the unmet needs in tobacco control efforts, particularly among youth and certain communities. The youth leaders met with Senator Rachel May, Assembly member Marianne Buttenschon and the staff representative of John Salka to discuss these important topics.

Photos L to R: BRiDGES Community Engagement Coordinator, Sue Casanova, Bailey Foster, Assembly member, Marianne Buttenschon, Adam Wojsiat, Joshua Drake, Rachel Mennig, BRiDGES Reality Check Coordinator, Kacy Brink.

https://www.uticaod.com/news/20200214/youth-discuss-tobacco-control-with-state-lawmakers

BRiDGES and Herkimer, Madison and Oneida county Reality Check youth were at the Capitol February 4, 2020, talking with lawmakers about the success of the state‚Äôs Tobacco Control Program about lowering the average smoking rate to 12.8%. They also talked about the unmet needs in tobacco control efforts, particularly among youth and certain communities. The youth leaders met with Senator Rachel May, Assembly member Marianne Buttenschon and the staff representative of John Salka to discuss these important topics.

Photos L to R: BRiDGES Community Engagement Coordinator, Sue Casanova, Bailey Foster, Assembly member, Marianne Buttenschon, Adam Wojsiat, Joshua Drake, Rachel Mennig, BRiDGES Reality Check Coordinator, Kacy Brink.

post_text: At Stockbridge Valley Central School, the safety of our students and staff is our highest priority. A Hold-In-Place was used today (January 21st) at Stockbridge Valley. A Hold-in-Place is used to limit the movement of students and staff during an internal incident, such as a medical emergency or a maintenance issue. Outer doors are locked during a Hold-In-Place, but classes continue as normal inside. All students and staff were safe during the Hold-In-Place, which lasted approximately 20 minutes.
